entry.title: Suppress possible double-counting of the UMA for input suppression
entry.content:
Behind a flag we already have a fix for the bug. The fix suppresses

input to the page until first paint signal arrives. Before we flip

the flag, we want to make sure that the topmost frame always receives

the signal, in order to rule out the possibility of input event starvation.



The UMA data seems to have a problem, we encountered too many

occurrences for PageLoad.Internal.SuppressedEventsTimingBeforePaint2

when max-delay is reached. This CL fixes two possible causes of the anomaly:



- If WIHM is re-used across a navigation, the max-delay timer was not

reset, and this possibly caused wrongly counting such a navigation

if it happened within 15 sec.



- We are suspecting that the `first_paint_time` received by

WIHM::RecordEventMetricsForPaintTiming maybe zero even when

max-delay is not reached. See comment#148 in the bug. To isolate

the UMA from being affected by this possibility, we are passing a

separate boolean parameter to indicate max-delay reached.



The CL also fixed uninitialized `suppressing_input_events_state_`, and renamed `WIHM::DidNavigate` to better reflect its purpose.

entry.title: [A11y] Fix regression in AXEventGenerator caused by stable ids
entry.content:
Skipping these events on nodes that are either remaining ignored,

were ignored, or are about to be ignored is a significant performance

win for the browser, and likely in ATs as well.



Ignored nodes are not exposed to ATs, and therefore firing change

events on them creates extra work without any benefit.



We were always paying this cost on some nodes, but it became worse

recently after landing stable ids CL:5328829. Previously when nodes

changed from ignored to ignored, the id often

also changed, which caused the AXNode to be a new node, and there was

no old vs new data to compare, preventing this code from running in

the first place.

entry.title: Implement Overlay logic for OpenXR on Android
entry.content:
Provides the infrastructure needed to support overlay code on Android:

* Creates a GraphicsDelegateAndroid and mechanism to create the correct

one (currently just a per-platform-defined static method, but this can

be revisited if need be in the future).

* Slight refactors to the GraphicsDelegate start-up flow, since Android

needs this to be asynchronous.

* Creates a VrUiHostImpl (and subsequently a VrBrowserRendererThreadWin)

on all platforms.

* Switches from a mojo::PlatformHandle to a GpuMemoryBufferHandle which

allows for sending AHardwareBuffers cross-process.



Also implements Overlays for OpenXR (since most of the infrastructure

was present), this involves removing a few BUILDFLAG guards and adding

an implementation to OpenXrGraphicsBindingOpenGLES.



A few items will be revisited in the future:

* The "You have a permission prompt waiting" dialog appears to be

commented out in UiSceneCreator. A future change will revisit this and

simplify VrBrowserRendererThreadWin based on what makes sense per-

platform.

* VrBrowserRendererThreadWin is no longer windows only and needs

renaming.



This does result in a fairly substantial binary size increase. After

talking with mthiesse@, gfx::RenderText (responsible for ~1/2 the

increase) is the only way to do text rendering in C++. Since this

code is also used on Desktop, we need to do this rendering in C++.

However, this increase is somewhat mitigated as the RenderText

OWNERS (etienneb@) would like to use some of this code on Android as

well. The other half of the increase appears to be due to the rest of

the element-specific code. Note that this code was previously on

Android, but included as part of the VR DFM. Some future changes may

pare this size down by a few more kb, as there appear to still be

some unused portions that are being built (but not many).

entry.title: [Extensions] Change when webview elements are exposed
entry.content:
There are a number of different tags that are exposed for webview

elements, including chromeWebViewElement () and

controlledFrame (). Because controlledFrame is built

atop the Chrome Web View implementation, contexts that may construct

controlledframes also necessarily have access to the

chromeWebViewInternal API.



This created an issue when exposing the elements themselves, since

contexts that are able to create controlledframes should *not* be

able to create webviews. The way this is handled today is by allowing

an ExtensionRendererAPIProvider to provide a webview module and, if

any provider provides one, not calling into the DispatcherDelegate to

provide one (which is where the chrome webview module is loaded).



This works, but is a bit clunky and subtle, and also introduces a few

limitations:

- It means there must be a "default" implementation, which makes it

difficult to move out logic from the

ChromeExtensionsDispatcherDelegate into the

ChromeExtensionsRendererAPIProvider.

- It means there is an implicit requirement that only one webview-

style element is exposed. Today, that's true, but it doesn't need

to be (in theory, we could have a world where extensions or webui

could also create controlledframes).



This CL refactors this by introducing a new feature into

_api_features.json, "chromeWebViewTag". This feature explicitly

controls the availability of the webview tag exposure, and is only

available to extensions/apps and webui (not to controlledframe

embedders). controlledframe embedders still have access to the

underlying chromeWebViewInternal API, as does everything for which

chromeWebViewTag is available.



This allows the registration of chromeWebViewElement and

controlledFrame to be fully independent of one another.

entry.title: Shadow including elements of a form must be hosted by descendants.
entry.content:
Prior to this CL, the collection of shadow including listed elements

of a form would sometimes happen too aggressively: If any listed

element inside light DOM had an explicit "form" attribute, then

collecting the shadow including listed elements of that form would

include all (unassociated) form control elements inside shadow DOM.



This CL ensures that only those listed elements inside shadow DOM

are included whose shadow host is a descendant of the form for which

listed elements are collected.

entry.title: feedback: Fix a UAF of FeedbackHandler::dialog_
entry.content:
The dialog_ is a raw_ptr which is passed in when the FeedbackHandler is

constructed:



`AddWebUIMessageHandler(std::make_unique(this));`



but the WebUIMessageHandler being constructed there does not have a

lifetime bound to the FeedbackDialog being passed in. The

WebUIMessageHandler is owned by the WebUI, and the WebUI is owned by a

RenderFrameHost, while the FeedbackDialog itself is self-owning and

destroys itself in response to the WebContents starting to close.



- Update FeedbackHandler to take a base::WeakPtr of a FeedbackDialog.

-login-manager --remote-debugging-port=9999`

4) Click "feedback" to inspect the chrome://feedback page,

5) In the Console tab, run: `setInterval(_ => { chrome.send("showDialog"); close() }, 0)`.

entry.title: [omnibox][ml] Implement ML URL score caching in ML scoring service.
entry.content:
Prior to this CL, the autocomplete machinery needed to generate the ML

scores associated with URL suggestions from scratch every time

`BatchScoreAutocompleteUrlMatchesSync()` was invoked. Given that

performing such ML inference on a frequent basis is a potentially costly

endeavor, it would be ideal to somehow cache the ML scores such that

repeat generations are not necessary when the same scoring signals (with

respect to a previous ML scoring run) are received as input by the ML

scoring service.



This CL implements the necessary cache infra needed to store ML scores,

such that the scoring service can now prioritize sourcing scores from

the cache (which is cheap) over generating them from scratch every time

(which is expensive). In addition to updating the scoring service to

make use of this cache, this CL also introduces the necessary feature

flags & params needed to enable this behavior in client code.

entry.title: [line-clamp] Make it possible to hide for paint non-table-cell boxes
entry.content:
`PhysicalFragment`s can be marked as hidden for paint, which makes

them invisible to paint regardless of `visibility` and other CSS

properties.



However, this is currently only used for hiding cells in a collapsed

table column, and while this can be set from `FragmentBuilder`, there

is no way to automatically set it from a constraint space. While there

is a `ConstraintSpace::IsTableCellHiddenForPaint`, besides being

specific to table cells and not generally applicable, it does not

automatically make fragments built from it hidden for paint.



Since line-clamp needs to be able to hide arbitrary boxes from paint,

this change changes the `ConstraintSpace` method to be a generic

`IsHiddenForPaint`, and makes the `FragmentBuilder` field default to

the constraint space's value.



This patch only refactors existing code and has no user-visible

effects.

entry.title: Make FrameSinkVideoCapturer supports RGBA with NativeTexture
entry.content:
Currently FrameSinkVideoCapturer only supports NV12 with

NativeTexture, I added format support for related codes and make it

also possible for RGBA.

Firstly, it is reasonable RenderableGpuMemoryBufferVideoFramePool

supports different formats, currently it is nailed to NV12 and cannot be

easily ported to other formats in future.

Also, with this change, the CEF OSR function can use shared GPU textures

to accelerate the paint. This function means greatly to CEF developers,

and I think it is better to make it goes into upstream Chromium instead

of a big patch. The Electron also wanted this for a long time. The OBS

also wanted this feature and they are stuck on M103 for a long time,

which might introduce possible security concerns.



https://bitbucket.org/chromiumembedded/cef/pull-requests/285

https://magpcss.org/ceforum/viewtopic.php?t=19404

https://github.com/electron/electron/issues/16961



Changes:



1. RenderableGpuMemoryBufferVideoFramePool supports multiple formats,

FrameSinkVideoCaptureImpl supports capturing RGBA use GMB mode,

VideoFramePool supports format-aware (GMB) and format-unaware

(SharedMemory) mode.

2. RenderableGpuMemoryBufferVideoFramePool use NV12 as default pixel

format to provide compability

3. DXGI GMB Factory supports BGRA_8888 texture

4. FrameSinkVideoCapturerImpl::DidCopyFrame supports GMB RGBA

5. Respect buffer_format_preference_ to recreate frame_pool_ when

FrameSinkVideoCapturerImpl::Start

6. FrameSinkVideoCaptureImpl use new GpuMemoryBufferVideoFramePool

7. Add test to `mojom::BufferFormatPreference::kPreferGpuMemoryBuffer + media::PIXEL_FORMAT_ARGB`
